1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,480
After launching my app and seeing no success, I rebuilt it and it made $80,000 in 6 months.

2
00:00:05,480 --> 00:00:11,720
Meet Praneeth, a builder from India who quit his software engineering job to go all in on building apps.

3
00:00:11,720 --> 00:00:16,560
But, after launching the first version of his app, he saw pretty much no success.

4
00:00:16,560 --> 00:00:20,360
So, he decided to make a simple pivot that changed everything.

5
00:00:20,360 --> 00:00:24,080
>> making 250k a year, but always knew I wanted to build my own thing.

6
00:00:24,080 --> 00:00:29,120
In this video, Praneeth will share what most builders get wrong about their first idea,

7
00:00:29,120 --> 00:00:37,240
the pricing change that made him $80,000 in 6 months, and specifically how you can price your first product so you can make money on day one.

8
00:00:37,240 --> 00:00:40,880
>> I would not recommend starting with a subscription model if you're bootstrapping.

9
00:00:40,880 --> 00:00:42,600
This one is going to be fun.

10
00:00:42,600 --> 00:00:45,640
I'm Pat Walls, and this is Starter Story.

11
00:00:45,640 --> 00:00:47,080
Praneeth, welcome to the channel.

12
00:00:47,080 --> 00:00:49,760
Tell me about who you are, what you built, and what's your story?

13
00:00:49,760 --> 00:00:55,520
My name is Praneeth, and I quit my $250,000 job last year and went all in on building my own apps.

14
00:00:55,520 --> 00:01:01,200
I built an app called Canvas Mode, which was formerly known as Rabbit Holes AI, but when I built the first version of it,

15
00:01:01,200 --> 00:01:02,400
it didn't get any traction.

16
00:01:02,400 --> 00:01:07,080
But then, I changed the pricing model and my app made $80,000 in the last 6 months.

17
00:01:07,080 --> 00:01:10,880
Okay, well, before we get into that pricing change, which I'm really excited to talk about,

18
00:01:10,880 --> 00:01:14,040
I do want to understand what is your business, what is Rabbit Holes?

19
00:01:14,040 --> 00:01:19,320
>> Rabbit Holes AI is an app which is basically a canvas-first way to interact with AI models.

20
00:01:19,320 --> 00:01:24,840
If you've ever chatted with ChatGPT for a really long time, it tends to kind of forget or loses place in the conversation.

21
00:01:24,840 --> 00:01:29,760
So, it's really hard to have any meaningful long conversations with a linear app like ChatGPT.

22
00:01:29,760 --> 00:01:38,000
So, what happens in a canvas app like this is as soon as you see something is kind of getting interesting and you want to branch off or create a different kind of fork in that conversation,

23
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:39,880
you can do that by creating a new node.

24
00:01:39,880 --> 00:01:46,040
So, Rabbit Holes AI is built for power AI users to get more out of the AI, unlike linear conversation apps.

25
00:01:46,040 --> 00:01:49,520
Okay, let's talk about how you came up with the idea for this.

26
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:51,640
Obviously, this app is huge, has lots of users.

27
00:01:51,640 --> 00:01:53,880
How did you find the idea to build this?

28
00:01:53,880 --> 00:01:59,320
>> I was initially trying to work on build on one of my old ideas, and I was using ChatGPT,

29
00:01:59,320 --> 00:02:03,080
and I was using Perplexity, and I was using Claude to do that to teach myself.

30
00:02:03,080 --> 00:02:06,800
I soon I found myself like distributed across a bunch of different tabs.

31
00:02:06,800 --> 00:02:09,000
Each one of those had different kind of expertise.

32
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:13,960
Claude was much better for coding, and GPT was much better for high-level architectural kind of things,

33
00:02:13,960 --> 00:02:17,240
and uh Perplexity was much better for real-time information.

34
00:02:17,240 --> 00:02:22,280
So, the UX designer in me thought, "Okay, this is a frictionless experience, and this is kind of broken,

35
00:02:22,280 --> 00:02:25,520
and I feel it's it's going to be much better if I can do it all in one tab."

36
00:02:25,520 --> 00:02:28,120
And it kind of evolved as a design from there.

37
00:02:28,120 --> 00:02:36,600
Okay, so, you have this idea, you start building it, but you sort of make almost a mistake when you start building it in terms of the pricing model.

38
00:02:36,600 --> 00:02:40,560
Can you tell me about when you started building it, what your plan was for how to price this thing,

39
00:02:40,560 --> 00:02:42,400
and kind of how that whole process started?

40
00:02:42,400 --> 00:02:49,200
>> The default mode of how I operated with bad building products was the typical subscription model or the freemium model.

41
00:02:49,200 --> 00:02:55,040
So, that's where I went with initially and launched a web app with free trial where you get like a few questions for free,

42
00:02:55,040 --> 00:02:59,600
and then you have to pay after a little bit of usage, but that didn't get much traction,

43
00:02:59,600 --> 00:03:01,800
and I feel like there is multiple reasons to that.

44
00:03:01,800 --> 00:03:10,440
The top ones are that I did not have a huge personal brand trying to do the building public thing where I was talking on Twitter or kind of posting everywhere where I got a chance.

45
00:03:10,440 --> 00:03:14,520
I got some interest, but never really turned into any real dollars.

46
00:03:14,520 --> 00:03:20,480
And on top of it, I kind of decided that my ideal customer profile, ICP, is a power AI user.

47
00:03:20,480 --> 00:03:27,120
So, at that point, my ICP would already be saturated with bunch of different subscriptions they are paying for these multiple AI models.

48
00:03:27,120 --> 00:03:34,760
So, that's when I had to change the product a little bit by moving away from web app into a and making it a one-time purchase.

49
00:03:34,760 --> 00:03:38,960
>> Okay, so, you have this app, it's sort of working, you've got some users, you got free trials,

50
00:03:38,960 --> 00:03:42,200
but you feel like there's maybe something missing, and you make a change.

51
00:03:42,200 --> 00:03:45,960
Tell me about what that change was and what happened after you made that change.

52
00:03:45,960 --> 00:03:52,320
>> To balance all the things that were peculiar to my situation, I wanted to start with the one-time purchase,

53
00:03:52,320 --> 00:04:01,640
and I had to convert the app into a one-time purchase, which means that I cannot incur any AI cost because AI usage cost me money,

54
00:04:01,640 --> 00:04:04,320
and I wanted to offload that to the users.

55
00:04:04,320 --> 00:04:07,320
So, that was step one to make it bring your own keys.

56
00:04:07,320 --> 00:04:10,480
And the second step was to not even incur any server cost.

57
00:04:10,480 --> 00:04:16,560
If I were to like just build it once and sell it many times, I had to offload my server cost to the users as well.

58
00:04:16,560 --> 00:04:22,560
And the easiest way to do that was to just use the users'computers, and to do that, I had to build a desktop app.

59
00:04:22,560 --> 00:04:27,400
This allows me to like ship and forget about my business cost, and everything ran on the users.

60
00:04:27,400 --> 00:04:28,680
They paid for the AI.

61
00:04:28,680 --> 00:04:31,880
As soon as they changed it, a lot of people actually started paying.

62
00:04:31,880 --> 00:04:34,760
They were more serious in terms of giving feedback.

63
00:04:34,760 --> 00:04:42,880
It felt much more refreshing in the sense that people were not only more serious, but they were also more helpful in kind of like believing in this early-stage product.

64
00:04:42,880 --> 00:04:48,960
So, after we moved to a one-time purchase model, that change led to about $80,000 in the last 6 months.

65
00:04:48,960 --> 00:04:55,080
Okay, so, for anyone watching this, I do want to reiterate that a lifetime deal doesn't make sense for all businesses.

66
00:04:55,080 --> 00:04:59,400
So, I'd like to hear from you, when does a lifetime deal make sense?

67
00:04:59,400 --> 00:05:02,120
What type of business and what type of founder is this for?

68
00:05:02,120 --> 00:05:05,480
I think every bootstrap business should do an LTD model.

69
00:05:05,480 --> 00:05:12,800
The pricing and how they do it should obviously vary according to their unique product use cases and the costs that they incur,

70
00:05:12,800 --> 00:05:17,560
but I think a VC style of doing freemium would not work for a bootstrap model.

71
00:05:17,560 --> 00:05:22,880
Having venture capital would actually mean that you can offset your truth-seeking in essence,

72
00:05:22,880 --> 00:05:28,000
like you can kind of delay your product market fit, so you can kind of hope that people would come on board,

73
00:05:28,000 --> 00:05:31,440
but that's not a luxury that bootstrap businesses would have.

74
00:05:31,440 --> 00:05:36,120
So, almost every bootstrap business should do a lifetime deal along with whatever they are doing.

75
00:05:36,120 --> 00:05:39,680
If you already have like a subscription model, have a lifetime deal.

76
00:05:39,680 --> 00:05:45,880
Even if it's a limited thing, have it because it kind of gives you this boost in morale with this chunk of cash coming in,

77
00:05:45,880 --> 00:05:53,840
and you have a much more validated idea, and you have a good sizable user base who are willing to actively give feedback and be involved,

78
00:05:53,840 --> 00:06:01,960
and it's hugely, hugely beneficial if you're a solo founder or like a founder with like a small team trying to figure out what to build because usually what happens,

79
00:06:01,960 --> 00:06:08,000
which happened with me in the past as well, was that you kind of get into your own head and trying to think what to build and what not to build.

80
00:06:08,000 --> 00:06:12,400
All right, before we get into how Praneeth successfully pivoted and relaunched his business,

81
00:06:12,400 --> 00:06:13,880
I do need to point something out.

82
00:06:13,880 --> 00:06:17,640
Making money online isn't as complicated as most people think.

83
00:06:17,640 --> 00:06:22,840
At its core, it's as simple as creating something valuable and putting a Stripe payment link on it.

84
00:06:22,840 --> 00:06:26,880
No, it won't always work, but you'll never know unless you ship it.

85
00:06:26,880 --> 00:06:28,880
And that's the beauty of the internet today.

86
00:06:28,880 --> 00:06:33,840
There are almost no barriers to try, and this is why we created a Starter Story Build.

87
00:06:33,840 --> 00:06:38,720
It's our action-oriented bootcamp where in just a couple of weeks, you'll come up with an idea,

88
00:06:38,720 --> 00:06:42,560
you'll build it with AI tools, and you'll actually launch it to the real world.

89
00:06:42,560 --> 00:06:48,600
Even if you have no coding experience or you're still working a full-time job, there has never been a better time to just try.

90
00:06:48,600 --> 00:06:53,560
So, if you're ready to take action, click the first link in the description to learn more about Starter Story Build.

91
00:06:53,560 --> 00:06:55,480
All right, now back to Praneeth's story.

92
00:06:55,480 --> 00:06:59,560
The next question I have is more specific and tactical is the pricing of lifetime deal.

93
00:06:59,560 --> 00:07:05,480
How did you price your lifetime deal, and how would you recommend anybody who's got similar products to price a lifetime deal?

94
00:07:05,480 --> 00:07:11,520
If you are building an AI product, I think it's absolutely worth it to have a bring-your-own-keys model.

95
00:07:11,520 --> 00:07:17,040
That offsets a lot of costs, and it kind of offloads it from you to the users, so everybody should do that.

96
00:07:17,040 --> 00:07:23,240
The way I've done that for Rabbit Holes is that the pricing of the actual product actually started with something really small.

97
00:07:23,240 --> 00:07:26,760
I started off with $29 when I was under 100 users.

98
00:07:26,760 --> 00:07:36,920
Once it crossed 100, I bumped it to like 49, and we are going to be bumping the lifetime deal much higher and kind of moving on to a recurring model now that we are about uh 1,200 users right now.

99
00:07:36,920 --> 00:07:43,400
So, the initial offering was much lower, and the early users who bought in got a much better deal.

100
00:07:43,400 --> 00:07:48,040
And it also gave me feedback of like it that the market is wanting to buy something like this.

101
00:07:48,040 --> 00:07:50,880
On that tactical note, I do also want to talk about growth.

102
00:07:50,880 --> 00:07:55,520
Yes, you can create a lifetime deal, and you can set your pricing, but you still need to drive users to the page,

103
00:07:55,520 --> 00:07:57,360
you still need to get it in front of people.

104
00:07:57,360 --> 00:08:01,360
How did you grow Rabbit Holes, and what was your growth strategies?

105
00:08:01,360 --> 00:08:05,560
One of the first things I would still want people to do is to get their landing page right.

106
00:08:05,560 --> 00:08:10,040
Um to get that right, I need think this is something that I've done in my past experiments,

107
00:08:10,040 --> 00:08:13,360
but this time I've done it right, which is to get my ICP correct.

108
00:08:13,360 --> 00:08:15,360
In my case, it was power AI users.

109
00:08:15,360 --> 00:08:19,240
So, my landing page copy was like completely tailored to power AI users.

110
00:08:19,240 --> 00:08:24,840
I call them out in my H1, and I call them out in multiple places on my website, and this is very important,

111
00:08:24,840 --> 00:08:28,440
and there's like tons of places where you can find how to structure your website.

112
00:08:28,440 --> 00:08:39,240
And after I've done that, I started like talking more about it on Twitter, and and I kind of like replied to conversations that were in relation to AI interactions and the new age of AI,

113
00:08:39,240 --> 00:08:45,480
and it was not just directly talking about my product in a sense, like, you know, buy my product or I'm building this and that sense,

114
00:08:45,480 --> 00:08:48,520
but I was just hinting towards something related to my product.

115
00:08:48,520 --> 00:08:51,720
>> On that note, I'd love to hear just some of the numbers of the business today.

116
00:08:51,720 --> 00:08:54,760
What is the business look like, revenue, profit, users?

117
00:08:54,760 --> 00:08:55,560
What can you share?

118
00:08:55,560 --> 00:09:03,320
It's like around 80k-ish in gross revenue as we speak, and about 75 around uh profits,

119
00:09:03,320 --> 00:09:05,720
and minus the refunds and everything.

120
00:09:05,720 --> 00:09:16,160
We are about like 1,200 paying users, and 60% of them are lifetime users, and about 40% are like people who bought it out of one-time purchase where they would have to renew

121
00:09:16,160 --> 00:09:18,680
it after a year to get more updates.

122
00:09:18,680 --> 00:09:23,920
And uh overall, we have about like 38,000 unique visitors to the site so far.

123
00:09:23,920 --> 00:09:24,960
Well, thanks for sharing that.

124
00:09:24,960 --> 00:09:26,920
On that same note, tell me about tech stack.

125
00:09:26,920 --> 00:09:28,200
How did you actually build this?

126
00:09:28,200 --> 00:09:35,280
I was saying in the beginning, I used AI as my co-founder in essence, and I used Cursor for coding.

127
00:09:35,280 --> 00:09:37,320
The landing page is built on Next.js.

128
00:09:37,320 --> 00:09:43,600
The actual app is an Electron app, and it's uh uses React underneath and um TypeScript to do it.

129
00:09:43,600 --> 00:09:46,680
And do you host the apps on Cloudflare, but that's not a huge deal.

130
00:09:46,680 --> 00:09:52,960
But another big thing I have to talk about or touch on is the AI SDK that is built by people at Vercel,

131
00:09:52,960 --> 00:10:04,720
and it's a huge accelerant in me being able to build this product because it allowed me to build a product with great abstraction where I could just focus on the front end and have almost nothing to

132
00:10:04,720 --> 00:10:08,560
worry about integrating with these multiple different kind of AI providers.

133
00:10:08,560 --> 00:10:11,480
AI SDK gives you the best abstraction in that sense.

134
00:10:11,480 --> 00:10:17,480
You use it and you're automatically capable of logging into all the top providers and then some.

135
00:10:17,480 --> 00:10:26,240
On a similar note, what I think is cool is you have this BYOK, bring your own keys, which basically means you don't have to pay for API LLM costs.

136
00:10:26,240 --> 00:10:30,440
So, I'm curious, what are the costs and margins for a business like this?

137
00:10:30,440 --> 00:10:35,320
You really don't have big server costs and you don't have API costs, so what does it cost to run day-to-day?

138
00:10:35,320 --> 00:10:36,880
It's almost nothing.

139
00:10:36,880 --> 00:10:43,560
I only have to pay for my landing page hosting and almost I can bring it to zero, but because I'm like a Next.js spoiled person,

140
00:10:43,560 --> 00:10:52,520
I host it on Vercel and I have some fancy things going on there, so it cost me about $50 a month and I have a Cursor subscription about $200 a month.

141
00:10:52,520 --> 00:10:57,160
But, that is something that I have to only spend because I have to keep working on new features,

142
00:10:57,160 --> 00:10:59,280
not to maintain the existing product.

143
00:10:59,280 --> 00:10:59,720
Cool.

144
00:10:59,720 --> 00:11:03,400
Well, last question that I have for you, a question that we ask all founders to come on to the channel.

145
00:11:03,400 --> 00:11:10,839
If you could stand on Praneeth's shoulder when you were just starting out before you had product market fit in this awesome product that's made a bunch of revenue,

146
00:11:10,839 --> 00:11:11,880
what would be your advice?

147
00:11:11,880 --> 00:11:18,360
I've been trying building different products since the last 6-7 years and for the good chunk of last 5 years,

148
00:11:18,360 --> 00:11:20,839
I was operating as a skills man.

149
00:11:20,839 --> 00:11:29,240
As an entrepreneur, your goal is to find product market fit as soon as possible and your goal is to build something that makes people's lives better,

150
00:11:29,240 --> 00:11:39,760
but what I was doing was appealing to my peers, which is totally not the mindset that I need to have as an entrepreneur because your whole purpose should be about finding a product market fit,

151
00:11:39,760 --> 00:11:49,520
finding something that you're going to put out in the market and they're going to give you money and reward you in return as a thank you for making their lives better and that should be your only goal.

152
00:11:49,520 --> 00:11:50,560
That's really good advice.

153
00:11:50,560 --> 00:11:51,800
Thanks for sharing that, Praneeth.

154
00:11:51,800 --> 00:11:52,440
That was awesome.

155
00:11:52,440 --> 00:11:53,680
Thanks for coming on to the channel.

156
00:11:53,680 --> 00:11:55,200
What you built is awesome.

157
00:11:55,200 --> 00:11:58,240
I'm excited to see what you continue to do and continue to build.

158
00:11:58,240 --> 00:11:58,920
Thanks for coming on.

159
00:11:58,920 --> 00:12:00,080
And thanks for having me.

160
00:12:00,080 --> 00:12:01,280
It's a great pleasure.

161
00:12:01,280 --> 00:12:03,360
All right, thank you Praneeth for coming on to the channel.

